                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p rend=\"align(right)\"><placeName>Richmond</placeName>, <date>January\n                                                  22.1849</date>.</p>\n                              <p>\n                                        <addressee>Revrd. Isaac Leeser</addressee>\n                              </p>\n                              <p rend=\"indent(2)\">Respected Friend,</p>\n                              <p rend=\"indent(5)\">It seems that<lb/> you have not read my letter as\n                                        I intended &amp; that I<lb/> have alarmed you unnecessarily.\n                                        I did not intend to<lb/> communicate the information that ll\n                                        of your Claims<lb/> here were offsetted by <persName>Jacob\n                                                  Ezekiel's</persName> indebtedness<lb/> but that\n                                        some were perhaps in that condition &amp; others<lb/> could\n                                        not be collected from other causes inability deaths<lb/>\n                                        &amp;c; and also my remarks about your matters\n                                        remaining<lb/> in <persName>Ezekiel's</persName> hands, were\n                                        not intended to charge him<lb/> with dishonesty, but meant\n                                        that your matters could not<lb/> prosper in the hands of\n                                        such an agent, who (it is<lb/> evident to me) has been very\n                                        luke-warm in your interest<lb/> to say the least. I have no\n                                        doubt in the hands of some<lb/> enterprising person your\n                                        interests could be largely aug-<lb/>-mented, as I wrote in\n                                        my previous letter. As regards<lb/> the claim you hold\n                                        against me, I did not wish to use<lb/> any plea to get off,\n                                        but was under the impression that<lb/>\n                                        <persName>Ezekiel</persName> had given me credit for the\n                                        amount and made<lb/> correct returns to you for the\n                                                  <sic>ammount</sic> for I feel fully satisfied that\n                                        I<lb/> have paid him for some volumes of the Occident in\n                                        cash<lb/> &amp; have his receipt, but cannot put my hand on\n                                        it at<lb/> this moment, notwithstanding I will pay what I\n                                        owe you<lb/> as it is hard for you to loose under either circumstances,<lb/>\n                                        <persName>Ezekiel</persName> owes me so much, he can owe me\n                                        a little more</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p33r0q945/canvas/p1"
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
